      "label": "Transcript",
      "value": "[Page One]\nWar Department\nJune 1, 1824\nTo Brigr. [Brigadier] Genl. [General] H. Atkinson \n[and]\nMajr. [Major] Benjamin O’Fallon\nGentlemen,\nThe President by virtue of the Act \nof Congress of the 26th ultims[?] authorizing him to appoint \nsuitable persons for Commissioners to negotiate Treaty of \nTrade and Friendship with the Indian Tribes beyond the \nMississippi and to fix their compensation and, has appointed \nyou to the execution of this trust.  Your commission \nis herewith enclosed. By the same act, the sum \nof ten thousand dollars is appropriated to carry this object \ninto effect. The design of Congress being expressed in \nthe act, (a copy of which I herewith transmit to you) it \nis not deemed to be necessary to dwell in detail upon \nthe objects to be effected.\nYou will exercise a sound discretion in the \nprosecution of this undertaking; and accomplish whatever \nmay be deemed by you to be necessary in carrying \nthe views of the government, as these are conveyed to \nyou by the act of Congress, into effect.\nThe sum appropriated, viz ten thousand dollars \nis intended to cover all expenses excepting those \nconnected with the military escort for which provision \nis made) as well those embraced by your com\n[Page Two] \nCompensation as commissioners, which will be to \nGenl. [General] Atkinson, [“for a time actually employed,” is written above line with as later addition with caret denoting location] a sum equal to the difference between \nhis present pay, and the pay and emoluments of his \nBrevel Bank[?]; to Major O’Fallon a sum which added to \nhis present pay as agent, will make it equal to \nGenl. [General] Atkinson; and to the Secretary five dollars \na day, on accounts made out in the usual forms, \naccompanied by your certificate of honor that \nthe sums to each, respectively are for services \nrendered under the commission.\nThe time of entering upon this commission \nis left to your discretion; but the sooner the duty \nassigned to you can be accomplished, the better,-- \nif it be practicable, this summer or autumn,-- \nbut if not, at the earliest period thereafter which \nit may be within your power to command.\nYour bills on this Department as you may \nfind it necessary to make them from time to time, \nto carry into effect this Commission, will be duty \npaid. You will preserve in distinct forms the \nvarious kinds of expenditure under the appropriate \nheads of present, military escort, pay of Commissioners,-- \nSecetary -- etc. etc.[?] which you may make, and so \nexpress it in your letters of advice, also; making \nthem      \n[Page Three]        \nthem to correspond with the payments in the\nseveral branches of the expenditure.\nThe bills will be sold at the market\nValue, and if there should be a premium it\nWill be accounted for to the Government.\nI have the honor to be\nVery respectfully\n[illegible]\nJ. C. Calhoun\nP.S. Your Commissioner not having been\n[illegible]. From the State Dept. [Department] will\nfollow [next?] mail.\n[Page Four]\nJ. C. Calhoun\n1824\nPresented to J. A. Manson\nby Wm. [William] de B. [Fryer?] Nov. [November] 1867"
